    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="1614"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1614">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.93/70.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Minister
                            <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 1, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 25. Conditions in Mexico appear to be much improved and it is not
                    believed that Chinese or other foreigners are in danger. No Chinese have been
                    molested so far as Department is able to learn. Do not believe they will be in
                    any danger in Mexico City. You may say to Chinese Government that this
                    Government will do everything within its power to protect Chinese in Mexico.
                    Department has been conferring with Chinese Legation here relative to giving
                    temporary asylum in United States to Chinese at Durango and Ensenada in case it
                    should become necessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
